  "cleanText": "The sower walked among the seeds held in his hand. Some fell upon the pathway, some on the rocky land. The birds came down, took them before they could take hold. On stony, barren quickly, then withered in the cold. The thorns rose up and choked them, no fruit was ever found. The seed that fell on good earth bore a hundred for a crown. Don't you worry for your life, for the things that come and go. See the birds up in the sky, they don't reap and they don't sow. Seek ye first for the kingdom and the rest will find its way. Knock upon the door, it opens, ask and you receive today. You can worry night and day, but tell me what it's worth. You cannot add a single hour to your time here on the earth. The lilies in the meadow, they do not weave or sew. Yet no king in all his splendor was ever dressed just so. Don't you worry for your life, for the things that come and go. See the birds up in the sky, they don't reap and they don't sow. Seek ye first for the kingdom and the rest will find its way. Knock upon the door, it opens, ask and you receive today. Ask and you'll be given, seek and you will see. Knock against the dark and the door will set you free. So great was all his love that he gave his only son, whoever believes lives forever. The grave will hold no one. Don't you worry, don't you worry, set the burden down. The seed in you is rising on the good and solid ground. Solid ground."
